commentBody:
@Paul 

Yesterday’s puzzle falling on a Wednesday told me something unique had to be coming the next day, and here it is!

I found it to be quite clever, and I think most of our expert commenters will, too, but the afternoon comments of the stragglers tomorrow will tend to be angrier and blame-ridden. Some people don’t believe their failure to figure out the gimmick could be their fault; it has to be the puzzle!

@Fact Boy

My mom used to make SOS, although of course she never called it that.  
When my big brother came home from the army he almost choked when he served it for lunch. My mother never knew the term, but the rest of us loved it.

@Fact Boy 

I think there might be a slight odor to elemental sulfur, owing to reacting with oxygen to form tiny amounts of sulfur oxides, some of which are really smelly.

But true, what is being smelled is not the elemental sulfur.

@Cat Lady Margaret 

Fashion advice for men’s pants: Don’t use the pockets. 

That’s a rule I frequently violate.

@Cat Lady Margaret 

Thank you! There are designers who apparently think we don't want them. Hear this, designers: you are wrong! 

RIP Liz Claiborne, who designed stylish, practical clothing for working women. The pants had nice deep pockets.

@Cat Lady Margaret
I won't buy pants that don't have pockets.

The real problem with women's pants is that they assume everyone is the same height, no matter how big around they are.  Why do men's pants come in waist/length and not women's?  LandsEnd catalog is the only place I can buy pants for my 34" inseam need.

@David Connell 

I frequently saw crews rowing on Lady Bird Lake in Austin, but they never to my memory wore jackets. They’d probably have been too warm. 

Cycling jackets and jerseys also often pockets on the back.

@Long walks n sunsets 
Well, that’s a type of glove that the protagonist of the referenced show probably never used!

(Kidding—I don’t think that’s a mainstream LDS prohibition, even though even monogamous families of that faith tend to be large, and the character was portrayed as having largely modern mores apart from the obvious, in contrast to his outright fundamentalist relatives.)

@john ezra
Not to nitpick, but "fête accomplit" means accomplished celebration.

You are looking for the idiom "fait accomplit" , which means mission accomplished or it's a done deed.

@Andrew 

I just snorted out my coffee. 

Miss the old gang!

@Vaer 

For some reason, I had trouble getting it to come up by searching the Wordplay archives. If anyone else is still looking, I got it via a Google search on "June 30, 2018 Wordplay." The July 1 threads are there.

I was working the puzzle back then, but that was years before I started reading Wordplay. Thank you for the tip! This was fun.

@Puzzlemucker 

I asked David about that when his last NYT puzzle ran. He told me he would still be editing the Universal crossword puzzles, but that he didn’t want to spend as much time on construction. That’s understandable, given that he was about 13 or 14 when he made his NYT debut. 

For anyone who has never done the Universal puzzles, give them a shot! They tend to be clued more gently than the NYT puzzles, but the themes are often just as much fun.

@Jim 

Yes, some further reading and introspection is called for on your part.  Elaborate and complicated and overwrought don't mean hard or difficult or challenging or clever.  At all.  They mean elaborate and complicated.  :)

My message is clear and consistent but your interpretation seems confused.  So yes I asked for more difficuly.  I wish you would read more carefully.

@sotto voce 

I loved my 96 Jetta too, it had the road feel of a BMW.   

Thinking about your story do you remember if the motor officer was wearing jodhpurs? Yes folks this once was common for motorcycle cops; maybe some still wear them. I think they now call them breeches though.

@Sloop 

How could have a front wheel drive car have had the road feel of a rear wheel drive one? I'm a sucker for a RWD auto, and specifically because it handles so differently on the road. Am I misunderstanding "road feel" perhaps?

I do like a VW too, FWD and all. A Golf is one of our two cars and it's amazing how fast, comfortable, practical, reliable and economical it is, especially for its size and price.

@Warren 

I will save Ms Rodriguez and Mr Gilmore for later so as not to wake my husband (who slept poorly Tuesday night). Thanks for the link. 

But I wanted to recommend a live version of “Long Black Veil” by Chip Taylor and Carrie Rodriguez. It was recorded at some festival in Germany and is one of the best versions of that song that I know.

@Andrzej 

Jettas and BMWs both have the road feel of a sports car, as opposed to the floating ocean liner feel of the old behemoth American sedans or the jolting ride of trucks or the sluggish performance of econo boxes.

The road-feel difference between FWD and RWD cars would be a deeper level of discernment.

@Sloop 

That's really nice that you know what I'm talking about, though I think the VR6 was a bit grittier.

But my boyfriend at the time had a Jetta as well, and his was definitely smooth - and i did mistake it for a BMW the first time I rode in it!

@sotto voce 

Thank you. Even when I don’t post, surely you must recognize my reco’s.

I’ve been having attitude issues, so I’m trying my hardest (obviously not perfectly) to keep them offline. Today’s posts were my attempt at seeing the glass as a little full.

@Min 

"We were up at five, had breakfast, then back in bed by six."

"I love my cigar, too, but I take it out once in a while."

@Jin No, it doesn't "work" because BIU is not the name of a show, nor is GOTOU something that happens in a football game. 

Rebuses are dumb enough, but if they're implemented in such a way that the multi-letter square works in both directions at least it's still CLOSE to being a crossword.

That's not what's happening here. This is a grid that requires different entires for across and down in the same square, which means the gird is broken -- and isn't a crossword at all.

@Andrzej 

You know it.  What a train wreck that was.  Oh, let me turn my head and cough and re-enter some letters in just the right way and I can finally be rid of this witless thing.

Sorry, you gave me flashbacks.  :)

@Andrzej 

In either version of football, basketball, hockey or a variety of other sports, when a defender is guarding you and you have managed to move a good distance from him or her so you could receive a pass, you GOT OPEN. 

(I assume that’s the sports thing, right?)

@Francis 

I wrote a reply to Stave L before, but the emus ate it.

Religion, horrible people, miserable people - those are some of my least favorite things, so I'll pass.

@Sam Lyons 

Not to make you jealous, but I’m at the Silverfork Lodge in Big Cottonwood Canyon. We’re on the highway side, so it won’t be long before the stream of cars heading to Brighton and Solitude starts. 

If it’s any consolation, the snow is hard, hard, hard. I heard that nasty scritchy sound on trails at Brighton that are usually powder runs. It’s still fun, though.

@Eric Hougland 

For a moment my (instantly very, very jealous) eyes read, “It’s  snowing hard, hard, hard,” and my heart did that little flip it used to do when I’d wake up on a whiteout morning and immediately know that I’d be skipping class that day. 

Hard snow notwithstanding, I hope you guys have an amazing time. I’m smiling at you through homesick tea… no, wait, it’s not tears, it’s the damn rain again.

@John/Lizziefish

Paper solvers or others who don't get the graphics for whatever reason can always go to xwordinfo.com and view the puzzle. If there are graphics or something else unusual, they will reproduce it or show something similar. 

<a href="https://www.xwordinfo.com/Crossword?date=2/27/2025" target="_blank">https://www.xwordinfo.com/Crossword?date=2/27/2025</a>

@Vaer 

Hear, hear for ROO and MOMOA. 

Bonus points to the puzzle for JODHPURS leading me to search for images from “Sunset Boulevard.” It was a hardship to wade through the pictures of a shirtless William Holden.

@M. Biggen 

Thanks for letting me know that. 

I don’t see how anyone who enjoys movies can not like Billy Wilder at his best — and “Sunset Boulevard” just might be it.

@Dan 
I wasn't meaning to complain. I just wondered if this is for me. 
There are crosswords that don't rely on trivia (however defined) or only rarely, and which focus on what is called here "wordplay" and I tend to feel that that is what a crossword is all about. I do really enjoy that aspect in this crossword.

@Jane Wheelaghan 
Just so you know:  after searing a BEEF ROAST, I put it in my "crockpot"/slow cooker with stock, wine, a onion and large carrot, herbs, and leave it for 6 hours.  Then it's refrigerated over night.  The next day, I defat the pot ROAST and give it several more hours before thickening the gravy.  
It's delicious, but with the price of beef just now, it shall be but a memory for quite some time!

@Jane Wheelaghan 
He spells it "Mickey"

Next time you'll know!!

@Mean Old Lady 

Sorry you don’t wish to spend your money on beef right now. 

Maybe you can substitute a nice egg dish? I know some great frittata recipes. :-)

@Eric Hougland

Eric, you are usually quite kind.  This type of flippant response about food prices (while you are off skiing, no less) comes off as quite privileged.  Some of us are on tight food budgets, simply trying to find protein at a reasonable price.  And we’re working the NYT xword via free access through the local library. 

Please think before you post.

@JCA 
Hang in there.
I gave Eric my Standard Smart-alecky Response (I hope).

@SP 

I'll even go to bat for gloves.  

When my dad worked, he often kept gloves in the back pocket of his work pants, which he called  dungarees, but they were basically jeans. When jeans became fashionable, the price of his works pants soared, even though his were not in the least stylish.

@Cathy 

I think that's the song of the day! Thanks for that! 

<a href="https://youtu.be/CUjIY_XxF1g?si=sGdht1C4agUH_1PZ" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/CUjIY_XxF1g?si=sGdht1C4agUH_1PZ</a>

@Deanosaur 

Maybe you have a mistake elsewhere in the grid.

I used U’s only and just imagined the objects in the pockets. That seemed to satisfy the software.

@Ernest 
Gardeners often have an edge.

ROMAs are a very sturdy "paste" variety, though they slice nicely as well.  I often took them to potlucks on a pretty green glass plate.

@HEK 
I never saw, never heard of, that show...  I got it only because I had figured out the  trick.  I was writing out the full "entry" in the margin (which I have because I am a print-and-pen person.  There ARE advantages.)

It sounds like total trash, but what else is new?  Or old?

@Beth R 
I've been complaining about this for a while, but there is a lack of consistency with how rebuses are entered. It's pretty frustrating when you've figured out the trick and know all the answers, but then have to figure out how to enter the rebus and complete the puzzle.

My greatest wish is that the programming team will come up with a set of rules for rebuses, and stick to it.

@Paul Chiampa 

Email the address at the top of the comments section, under the box in which you wrote your post. The support team is very accommodating. And pretty quick to respond. 

Good luck!

@Helen Wright 

Those answers are concealed in the pockets (U's). Or you could enter them as rebi, in which case they are not concealed. Your choice.

I liked imagining them inside the U's, so I did it that way.

@Chet 

Self-indulgent review based on lack of understanding of the trick and skill to solve the puzzle. Zero stars. 


Smh.

@Natdegu 

Yesterday's crossword had rebus-ish elements, variants.

Me three on yesterday's Strands, TV shows that I care not about.

@Linda Jo 

Me four on yesterday's strands. Don't know how many hints I used--lost count.

Once I figured out the theme, I knew I wouldn't know the rest.

@Barry Ancona 

And stay tuned. I believe both the city and the state passed bans (well, phase outs). I’m pretty sure the state law is being challenged in federal court (as federally preempted, perhaps?). Not sure about the city ban. And we know who’s now in charge at the federal level.  Well, Elon, but he lets the other guy have a lot of say.  And then there’s Zeldin now at the EPA who opposed the ban.  So, stay tuned.

Now, that’s not to say how much gas will be available downstate for new hookups without new pipelines…

@Eric 
Read more.

Emus: understand more.

@Eric it's a kind of pants for equestrians. 

I can understand some not liking "Thursday" wordplay quirks in crossword puzzles; sometimes I get why people are annoyed at having to confront the meaning of particular words in crossword puzzles, though usually I don't; and I can definitely relate to problems they sometimes have with clue construction and its level of misdirection.

But I really don't understand disliking an unfamiliar word, or calling a certain fact "trivia" when it happens to be outside one's existing knowledge base. Oh well.

@Go Yankees 

OMG.  You CANNOT have that username and be from Minnesota.  Don't you know what the Yanks have done to the Twins playoff hopes over the years???

Blasphemy.

@JD 

Smart! Scanning the column first is a reasonable  technique for balancing the frustration of a tricky solve with your need for distraction/escape/enjoyment. Sometimes you can only tolerate so much angst. Juggle your solving helps as you need.

cue Sinatra, I Did It My Way . . .

